Leif Johansson <leifj@sunet.se> wrote
Tue, 26 Mar 2013 10:26:50 +0100:

| On 03/26/2013 09:40 AM, Randy Bush wrote:
| >> the tor network, being an overlay, makes NATs disappear if we manage
| >> to address tamias nodes using tor network addresses (aka onions)
| > if there is a tor exit behind the nats, yes

Tor Hidden Services (HS) don't need exit relays.

A client running a HS anonymously announces its identity together with a
short list of relays it's picked as introduction points (and tells the
introduction points about its service).

A client which wants to connect to a given HS picks a Rendezvous Point
(RP), connects to it (over Tor) and asks one of the HS's introduction
points to tell the HS to connect there. If the HS wants to, it connects
to the RP (over Tor) and traffic can be exchanged. Note that this is in
effect a 5-hop circuit. Expect latency.


| which would be true if you torify tamias

No.
